1 Overview: Spatial data wrangling and visualization

In this weekâs lecture, we learned a bit about projection and coordinate reference systems, types of spatial data, and investigating spatial autocorrelation using variograms. In this first part of lab weâll practice working with spatial data, then move on to variograms and spatial interpolation in the next part. Weâll look at point pattern analysis (exploring spatial clustering) next week.

Today, weâll use vector data (polygons, points) to practice reading in spatial data, checking & updating the CRS, and doing some wrangling and visualization.

Weâll use several datasets:

  • California County shapefile (ca_counties_tiger_2016.shp) from the US Census Bureauâs 2016 MAF/TIGER database (accessed here)
  • Red sesbania records (invasive species) from the CA DFW (accessed here)

2 California county outlines (polygons)

2.1 Read it in with read_sf

First, letâs read in the California county shapefile:

Code 
ca_counties_raw_sf <- read_sf(here("data", "ca_counties", "CA_Counties_TIGER2016.shp"))
# .shp file is the shape data file, whereas .dbf is the database with info about that shape, and .prj has coordinate reference system information. We NEED to have all those types of files in the folder! If are missing any of them, bad things will happen.

Note we only have to point to the .shp file, not all the others that are related. Theyâre all needed! read_sf automatically knows to look for them.

The geometry column is what defines the spatial component of the dataframe.

2.2 Do a bit of wrangling (and see sticky geometry!)

Use View(ca_counties) to check out what it contains. Letâs simplify it by first converting area to km2 instead of m2, then only keeping county name and area.

Code 
ca_counties_sf <- ca_counties_raw_sf %>% 
  janitor::clean_names() %>% # clean the names
  mutate(land_km2 = aland / 1e6) %>% # 1 km is 1m meters
  select(county = name, land_km2) #keep just the name and the land area
# but it will keep the spatial geometry column. Geometry is "sticky"!

Take a look at ca_counties_sf. We should notice something very important about a simple features (sf) object: it just assumes you want to keep the spatial information, and you can work with the rest of the data as if itâs a non-spatial data frame (and the spatial information just âsticksâ - hence the term âsticky geometryâ). So even though we only called (and renamed) name and aland in the select() function, we see that the geometry column still exists!

What if we wanted just the dataframe, without the geometry? Convert to dataframe and select out the geometry column:

Code 
ca_counties_df <- ca_counties_sf %>%
  as.data.frame() %>%
  select(-geometry)

2.4 Explore it visually

Plot the California counties using geom_sf(). Notice that we can update aesthetics just like we would for a regular ggplot object. Here, we update the color based on land area (and change the color gradient).

Code 
plot(ca_counties_sf)

Code 
### note: select a specific column to create a single map

ca_counties_sf %>% select(land_km2) %>% plot()

Code 
ggplot(data = ca_counties_sf) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = land_km2), color = "white", size = 0.1) +
  theme_void() + # gets rid of background lat/long and axes
  scale_fill_gradientn(colors = c("cyan","blue","purple"))

Notice what aesthetics we didnât have to specify here?

geom_sf knows to look for a column called geometry (or sometimes geom).

3.4 Spatial join

How can I go about joining these data so that I can find counts? Donât worryâ¦st_join() has you covered for spatial joins!

Code 
# mash them together based on geometry.
ca_sesb_sf <- st_join(ca_counties_sf, sesbania_3857_sf) 
# multipolygons with points in them


sesb_ca_sf <- st_join(sesbania_3857_sf, ca_counties_sf) # points within counties

Note: joining defaults to keeping the geometry of the first object, and adds the records of the second where they spatially overlap the first (but drops the geometry of the second). And then we can find counts (note: these are not counts for individual plants, but by record in the dataset) by county. We canât just count the rows (e.g., using count()) because some rows are counties with no records (and sesbania information is all NAs).

We can also join the other direction:

Code 
sesb_counties_sf <- sesbania_3857_sf %>% 
  st_join(ca_counties_sf)

3.5 Summarize observations by county

Keeping the CA polygonsâ¦

Code 
sesb_counts_sf <- ca_sesb_sf %>% 
  group_by(county) %>%

slice max, n = 1

filter so itâs just that county

plot with points

Code 
county_max <- sesb_counts_sf %>% 
  filter(n_records == max(n_records)) %>%
  pull(county)

  filter(county == county_max)

solano_sf <- ca_counties_sf %>%
  filter(county %in% county_max)


# Subset of sesbania point locations only in Solano County

county_max <- sesb_counts_sf %>%

  pull(county)

solano_sesb_sf <- sesb_counties_sf %>% 
  filter(county == county_max) ### what if two counties had the same max value?

  filter(county %in% county_max)

  geom_sf(data = solano_sf) + # plot the outline
  geom_sf(data = solano_sesb_sf, color = 'red') # plot the points

4 Making an interactive map with tmap

Sometimes weâll want to make a map interactive so that audience members can zoom in, explore different areas, etc. We can use the tmap package to create an interactive map. Letâs make one for our California counties (fill aesthetic by land area) with the red sesbania locations on top:

Code 
# Set the viewing mode to "interactive":
tmap_mode(mode = "view")

# Then make a map (with the polygon fill color updated by variable 'land_km2', updating the color palette to "BuGn"), then add another shape layer for the sesbania records (added as dots):
tm_shape(ca_counties_sf) +
  tm_fill("land_km2", palette = "BuGn") + # make filled polygons
  tm_shape(sesbania_sf) + # tmap will automatically convert 
  # to the same coordinate system!
  tm_dots() # make dots

See all kinds of other cool ways you can update your interactive tmaps.

See:

  • tmap vignettes
  • Chapter 8 in Robin Lovelaceâs âGeocomputation in Râ

library(tidyverse)

5 Overview: Spatial data wrangling and visualization

In this weekâs lecture, we learned a bit about projection and coordinate reference systems, types of spatial data, and investigating spatial autocorrelation using variograms. In this first part of lab weâll practice working with spatial data, then move on to variograms and spatial interpolation in the next part. Weâll look at point pattern analysis (exploring spatial clustering) next week.

Today, weâll use vector data (polygons, points) to practice reading in spatial data, checking & updating the CRS, and doing some wrangling and visualization.

Weâll use several datasets:

  • California County shapefile (ca_counties_tiger_2016.shp) from the US Census Bureauâs 2016 MAF/TIGER database (accessed here)
  • Red sesbania records (invasive species) from the CA DFW (accessed here)

Note: joining defaults to keeping the geometry of the first object, and adds the records of the second where they spatially overlap the first (but drops the geometry of the second). And then we can find counts (note: these are not counts for individual plants, but by record in the dataset) by county. We canât just count the rows (e.g., using count()) because some rows are counties with no records (and sesbania information is all NAs).

sesb_counts_sf <- ca_sesb_sf %>%

So we see that we can still use our usual wrangling skills! Letâs do a bit more for fun, just to prove that our existing wrangling skills still work with spatial data - the spatial information just sticks to it! Only plot the county with the greatest number of red sesbania records, and make a map of those locations (yeah there are many ways to do this).

7.5.1 Pseudocode here!

Code 
# Subset of sesbania point locations only in Solano County

county_max <- sesb_counts_sf %>%
  filter(n_records == max(n_records)) %>%
  pull(county)

### we appended the county names to Sesbania records earlier:
solano_sesb_sf <- sesb_counties_sf %>% 
  filter(county == county_max) ### what if two counties had the same max value?

# Only keep Solano polygon from California County data
solano_sf <- ca_counties_sf %>% 
  filter(county %in% county_max)

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = solano_sf) +
  geom_sf(data = solano_sesb_sf, color = 'red')

8 Making an interactive map with tmap

Sometimes weâll want to make a map interactive so that audience members can zoom in, explore different areas, etc. We can use the tmap package to create an interactive map. Letâs make one for our California counties (fill aesthetic by land area) with the red sesbania locations on top:

Code 
# Set the viewing mode to "interactive":
tmap_mode(mode = "view")

# Then make a map (with the polygon fill color updated by variable 'land_km2', updating the color palette to "BuGn"), then add another shape layer for the sesbania records (added as dots):
tm_shape(ca_counties_sf) +
  tm_fill("land_km2", palette = "BuGn") +
  tm_shape(sesbania_sf) +
  tm_dots()

See all kinds of other cool ways you can update your interactive tmaps.
